On the windowsill of a fifth‑floor apartment, a silver‑striped cat named Luma stretched herself into a perfect crescent, soaking in the last warm ribbon of afternoon light. Below her, the city hummed with traffic and hurried footsteps, but Luma watched it all with the calm detachment of a creature who understood she was above such chaos. Her tail flicked lazily as a pigeon landed on the opposite rooftop, and for a heartbeat her eyes sharpened, pupils narrowing into focused slits. Then, deciding the bird wasn’t worth the effort, she settled her chin onto her paws and closed her eyes, the picture of effortless elegance. In her world, nothing was urgent — everything came to her in its own time.